	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I see. I don't see a lot of use for that, but it's still nice to know.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">reading $2004 does <strong>not</strong> increment the address pointer ($2003) - only writing does that.</div><br />That's probably what allowed you to use $2004 for reverse-engineering the sprite fetch behaviour, right? I mean, if each one of your reads would increment the address, you'd pretty much screw the fetching process.</div>
<br />
<br />Not necessarily - the PPU uses a separate counter to address sprite memory during rendering, since $2003 affects how that counter is initialized on <em>every</em> scanline.

		

